</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The population of Jewish settlements in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza 
Strip has grown by 6,500 over last year's figures, despite the 20-month-old 
Palestinian uprising, the government said. The figures, released by the 
government-run Central Bureau of Statistics, show that Jewish settlements grew 
almost 400% more than Jerusalem, the second-fastest growing area. The bureau 
reported that 66,500 Jews lived in the occupied territories in late 1988, an 
increase of 10.3% over 1987. Settler leaders attributed the continued growth to 
right-wing activists moving to the occupied lands in a show of Jewish resolve 
to hold onto the disputed lands. However, in 1986, the year before the 
uprising, the settler population increased by 15.8%, the bureau said. 
