<P>
Business; Part 4; Page 5; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
470 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GEIGER COUNTERS TO CHOCOLATE ROSES; 
</P>
<P>
TRADE FAIR AT UCI FEATURES FIRMS OWNED BY MINORITIES AND WOMEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES STROUSE, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1981, Doug Watt was an IBM service technician ready for a risk. He quit his 
job, opened a company called Best Business Machines in Laguna Niguel, and 
looked for business. 
</P>
<P>
Last month, Watt signed a $50,000 maintenance contract with UC Irvine, and by 
the end of the year he expects his company to sell $900,000 worth of business 
machines and service. Next year, sales should top $1 million, he said. 
</P>
<P>
While Watt's success is not uncommon in Orange County, one thing sets him 
apart: He's an American Indian. 
</P>
<P>
Watt was one of 55 vendors who gathered Thursday at UCI to peddle their wares 
at Spotlite '89, the university's second annual business trade fair for 
minority- and women-owned businesses. 
</P>
<P>
The event, Orange County's largest gathering of minority vendors, drew buyers 
from throughout Southern California to view products ranging from chocolate 
roses to Geiger counters. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the buyers represented companies or institutions that are required by 
the government to purchase some portion of their goods and services from 
minority-owned businesses. Among the shoppers were representatives from 
McDonnell Douglas and the University of California system. 
</P>
<P>
UC Irvine, probably the largest buyer at the show, leads California 
universities in purchases from minority businesses, according to Mel Davis, the 
university's small-business coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the university has spent 12% of its $30-million purchasing budget to 
buy laboratory equipment, sheets and towels, and more from minority businesses. 
About 7% has gone to minorities and 5% to women. 
</P>
<P>
Officials from UC Riverside attending the fair also said their campus spends 5% 
to 15% of their purchasing department's budget with minority businesses. 
</P>
<P>
"Just about everything here is something that we might buy," said Russ Lewis, 
UC Riverside's purchasing manager. "We've bought water purifiers, (book) 
binders and other things from companies that are here." 
</P>
<P>
Vendors at the show noted that sales only begin there; the real negotiations 
start after the booths are taken down. 
</P>
<P>
"We sell mostly to large groups like the university or corporations, so people 
don't make orders here," said Arlene Roach, senior account representative for 
Extend-A-Life, a 6-year-old Pasadena-based company which sells 
earthquake-survival kits. "They just want to ask questions about things." 
</P>
<P>
Other companies sold tools made by Latinos, graphic design by blacks and 
radioactive sensors by women. 
</P>
<P>
One of the show's biggest hits was a display of chocolate roses, chocolate 
false teeth, chocolate tool kits and even chocolate surfboards by the Chocolate 
Florist in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
"Several people today have bought chocolate computers," said Pat Pardoen, who 
opened the shop 1 1/2 years ago. "But mostly, they just look at the stuff and 
can't stop laughing, they like it so much." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Vendor Arlene Roach of Extend-A-Life shows the firm's 
earthquake-preparedness equipment. ; Photo, Business was brisk Thursday at 
UCI's second annual business trade fair for companies owned by minorities and 
women. RICK PERRY / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
