<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
RACE DRIVER KRUEGER TAKEN HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
INDIANAPOLIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Driver Phil Krueger was taken home to Indiana today from Michigan, where he was 
injured in the Marlboro 500 last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
Jon White, a spokesman for Methodist Hospital, said Krueger was admitted to the 
hospital's neuro-critical care unit this morning. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Steve Olvey, a specialist in race-related injuries, said Krueger was in 
good condition. 
</P>
<P>
"He is still unconscious, but he is beginning to respond to commands," White 
said, quoting the physician. 
</P>
<P>
Krueger, 38, of Indianapolis had been unconscious and in critical condition 
since Sunday, when his car struck a wall during the race in Brooklyn, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
Doctors in Michigan said Krueger suffered broken ribs, a broken left arm and 
head injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
